ğŸ” FIND YOUR SUBSCRIPTION NAME
Step 1: List All Subscriptions
powershell
# After logging in with az login
az account list --output table
Step 2: Look for Your Subscription
The output will show something like:

Name                               SubscriptionId                        TenantId
---------------------------------  ------------------------------------  ------------------------------------
Azure for Students                 12345678-1234-1234-1234-123456789012  abcdefgh-ijkl-mnop-qrst-uvwxyz123456
Pay-As-You-Go                     87654321-4321-4321-4321-210987654321  abcdefgh-ijkl-mnop-qrst-uvwxyz123456
Step 3: Set the Correct Subscription
powershell
# Use the exact Name from the list (copy-paste it)
az account set --subscription "Azure for Students"
# OR use the Subscription ID
az account set --subscription "12345678-1234-1234-1234-123456789012"
ğŸ¯ COMMON STUDENT SUBSCRIPTION NAMES
Your subscription might be called:

"Azure for Students"
"Azure for Students Starter"
"Microsoft Azure Sponsorship"
"Visual Studio Subscription"
âš¡ QUICK COMMANDS
powershell
# 1. Login (opens browser)
az login
# 2. List subscriptions
az account list --output table
# 3. Set your student subscription (replace with actual name)
az account set --subscription "Azure for Students"
# 4. Verify current subscription
az account show --query name -o tsv
ğŸ”§ IF YOU CAN'T FIND STUDENT SUBSCRIPTION
If you don't see a student subscription:

Check your email - Look for Azure student activation email
Activate student benefits - https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/free/students/
Create new student subscription - Follow the activation link
âœ… VERIFY YOU'RE USING THE RIGHT SUBSCRIPTION
powershell
# Check current subscription details
az account show
# Should show your student subscription with $200 credit
az consumption budget list --output table
The key is to copy the exact subscription name from the az account list output and use that in the az account set command.

